Section section_02 (Chars 8947–12876):
Section Summary: Herbert Spencer's philosophy was shaped by his early writings in the Nonconformist, which marked a shift from his life as an engineer to a life of philosophical inquiry. His work emphasized the philosophy of life and mind, but also encompassed a broader range of ideas, including evolution as a universal principle and the concept of law governing all aspects of existence. Spencer's philosophy was all-inclusive, covering biology, psychology, sociology, and ethics, and aimed to interpret all phenomena in terms of matter, motion, and force. He believed that even mental evolution could be explained in terms of the redistribution of matter and motion, and that consciousness could be resolved into units of consciousness and molecular oscillations. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy acknowledged the limits of human understanding, recognizing that some mysteries, such as the ultimate reality, may be unknowable.
